Inspired by both the brostep of yesteryear and his Christian faith, Seall aims to bring light to the bass music scene by promoting a wholesome lifestyle, musical uniqueness and exceptional production. To say this has caught on would be an understatement, as he has amassed more than 20 million streams on Spotify to date and earned cosigns from just about every A-list bass DJ one could imagine (not the least of which include Skrillex, Zomboy, Seven Lions, NGHTMRE, Flux Pavilion and SLANDER). He also regularly releases on prolific dance labels such as Monstercat, Ophelia, Disciple, NSD and Circus. 

Ace Aura is known for his high-energy DJ sets, which seamlessly flow between expertly-curated waves of dubstep, hardwave, trap and hardstyle, with a sprinkle of nostalgic pop cuts. His presence has graced more than a fair share of coveted stages, including Excision‚Äôs Lost Lands & Bass Canyon, Red Rocks Amphitheatre (as direct support for Subtronics), Electric Zoo and Wobbleland. There comes a time in every artist‚Äôs career when the art form transcends a mere outlet for self-expression and becomes a universal gift to mankind laced with the necessary genius of its creator. For some it takes years, for 27-year-old Abby Holliday it was there from the start, her vulnerable introspection and brutal lyricism combined with mind-bending sonic sensibilities and a distinct production style that immediately fused a bond between her and her loyal fan base that grows stronger every day. Hailing from Cincinnati, OH now residing in Nashville, TN, Holliday masterfully guides listeners through moments in time extremely specific to her own life that puts words to collective experiences of the human condition, reaching into places we might not have known existed prior. 

Having begun her musical journey on guitar, Abby found her voice during her early years of college where she began quietly writing songs in the confides of her room. After a friend heard the songs and encouraged her to record them, Abby met producer Jonathan Class and set off to record her debut WHEN WE‚ÄôRE FAR APART I FALL APART. It was in these studio moments where Abby‚Äôs sound began to take shape, a launchpad for her sophomore album I‚ÄôM OK NO I‚ÄôM NOT. While guitar naturally remains the centerpiece of many of her songs, Holliday and Class explore and experiment with a wide range of sounds from vocoded vocal stacks, to jarring synths, to lush strings and piano, to a tasteful blend of organic and synthetic rhythm sections amassing in a discography that runs the gambit of the most beautiful songs you‚Äôve ever heard to songs that smack you in the face with unforgettable hooks and driving beats. 

With an impressive touring history opening for acts like James Bay, Michigander, Phillip Phillips, The Wldlfe, and more, Abby isn‚Äôt after a viral moment or to be a flash in the pan. Rather, she understands the importance of grassroots building on a foundation on authenticity that naturally pours over into her music and live show. The effect is already placing her front and center of the new wave of indie alternative pop/singer-songwriter music.

His new EP Stargazing is an ode to the beauty of creation and exploring it with the people you love. "Everywhere I go I can't help but smile and admire the beauty around me, and that's what I wrote the Stargazing EP about," Everen said. "It's a call to see the magic and wonder in creation, an anthem for exploring the world with your favorite people, and a dream of what amazing things might come next." "It‚Äôs about the little eternities that exist in the world around us, it‚Äôs about the limitlessness of being, it‚Äôs about the joys that encompass the art of living, and it‚Äôs about the act of being present, truly present, to experience all of the above. Stonelands travels through various modes of Bliss, from bursts of euphoria and abandon on the more energetic pieces to the stillness and tranquility of others. A great deal of the record weaves through steady, repetitive motions and insistent vocalizations that all feel meditative, regardless of whether they are backdropped by a wall of enveloping sound or a wall of enveloping silence. Rather than trying to impress with sonic curves out of left field, Stonelands bucks the culture that its architect came from and asks you to sit and hold yourself in an introspective embrace. To listen for yourself in the sameness and silence, and to listen for your own voice ‚Äî the one that reminds you of who you are, of what hopes and dreams you have, and of the inner child who is beckoning you to fill with light. All of these moments when you allow yourself to feel it are like affirmations, as if the music is saying, 'You know I love you, right?'"

-Evelyn Y.
